 Hello everyone. So this isn’t exactly a problem but instead, something I haven’t found anywhere on the internet but on ChatGPT with a few prompts and I’d like to help people save their time. 
 Usually when you want to send a piece of information from the server to the client or vice-versa, you’d do something like: 
  --Side: Server.
local newSignal = Service.Client.CreateSignal();
newSignal:Fire(player, newInfo);

 And then: 
  --Side: Client
Service = Knit.GetService();
Service.newSignal:Connect(function(newInfo)
   print("Got new info:", newInfo);
end);

 Cool. But what if I want to similarly warn all my controllers (client side) that something on the client side happened that is interesting to many controllers? If I wasn’t clear enough, I’ll give you an example. 
I was trying to warn all my controllers (UIController, AimController, etc…) that the client connected a gamepad (device switch). That way, UIController could instantly change icons accordingly to the new device type. 
The solution is: We, naturally, have a InputController that listens to UserInputService.GamepadConnected/Disconnected. That exact same controller will create the signal and fire it when needed. 
  --Side: Client

function InputController:KnitStart()
    local function warnEveryone()
    --???
    end;
    UserInputService.GamepadConnected:Connect(warnEveryone)
    UserInputService.GamepadDisconnected:Connect(warnEveryone)
end;

 We can’t use Knit.CreateSignal() here, I’ve tried and it says that we tried to call a nil value. 
The solution is to go straight to the Packages.Signal module and use the ‘new’ function to manually create ourselves a signal like so: 
  --Side: Client
local SignalModule = require(ReplicatedStorage.Packages.Signal);


